# Gremlin UI — AI Coding Rules

## Token Usage
- NEVER use raw color values (hex, rgb, hsl). Use semantic tokens: `colors.fg.DEFAULT`, `colors.bg.surface`, `colors.accent.DEFAULT`
- NEVER use raw spacing values. Use the spacing scale: `spacing.1` (4px) through `spacing.12` (48px)
- For dark mode support, use semantic tokens — they swap automatically. Components should NEVER reference `colors.gray.900` directly.

## Component Patterns
- Use compound components for complex widgets. `<Autocomplete.Trigger>`, not `trigger={<Button />}` props
- Use `asChild` for polymorphism: `<Button asChild><a href="...">Link</a></Button>`, NOT `<Button as="a">`
- Every `<IconButton>` MUST have `aria-label`. TypeScript enforces this, but catch it before the type checker does.
- Wrap form inputs in `<FormField>` for automatic label/error/description association. Never wire `htmlFor` manually.

## Layout Components
- Use `<Stack>` for vertical flex layouts with gap (default gap="4")
- Use `<HStack>` for horizontal flex layouts with gap (default gap="3")
- Use `<Grid columns={N}>` for CSS grid layouts (default gap="4")
- Use `<Container>` for max-width centered containers (default maxWidth="lg", paddingX="6")
- Use `<Box>` for generic styled containers with padding/borderRadius props
- All layout components support `asChild` for polymorphism
- NEVER use raw `display: "flex"` or `display: "grid"` — use layout components instead

### Layout examples:
```tsx
<Container maxWidth="xl">
  <Stack gap="6">
    <HStack justify="between" align="center">
      <h1>Title</h1>
      <Button>Action</Button>
    </HStack>
    <Grid columns={3} gap="4">
      <Card />
      <Card />
      <Card />
    </Grid>
  </Stack>
</Container>
```

## Typography Components
- Use `<Text>` for all body text — renders `<p>` by default
- Use `<Text as="span">` for inline text inside other text elements
- Use `<Heading level={N}>` for all headings (h1–h6) — uses heading font automatically
- NEVER use raw `<p>`, `<h1>`, `<h2>`, etc. with manual css() typography — use Text/Heading instead
- NEVER nest `<Text>` (which renders `<p>`) inside another `<Text>` — use `<Text as="span">` for the inner one

### Typography examples:
```tsx
<Heading level={2} size="2xl" align="center">Section Title</Heading>
<Text size="sm" color="muted">Body text paragraph</Text>
<Text size="sm" color="muted" italic>
  Selected: <Text as="span" color="accent" weight="semibold">{value}</Text>
</Text>
<Text font="mono" size="xs" color="subtle">Code-like text</Text>
```

## Accessibility Requirements
- All interactive elements need `focus-visible` styling (handled by the component, but custom wrappers must preserve it)
- Use `aria-live="polite"` for dynamic content changes (search results, tag additions/removals)
- Test keyboard navigation: Arrow keys in Autocomplete, Escape to close popovers, Tab to move focus forward (never trap in dropdowns)

## Animation
- All motion uses system tokens: `durations.fast`, `easings.out`, etc.
- Always wrap animations in `_motionSafe` condition for `prefers-reduced-motion` respect
- CSS-only animations. No Framer Motion.

## Nav Component
- Compound component: `<Nav>` > `<Nav.Section>` > `<Nav.Item>`
- `Nav.Section` takes a `title` prop for section labels
- `Nav.Item` supports `active`, `badge`, and `asChild` props
- Use `asChild` with your router's NavLink for active state management
- Designed for sidebar navigation patterns

### Nav example:
```tsx
<Nav>
  <Nav.Section title="Overview">
    <Nav.Item asChild active>
      <NavLink to="/dashboard">Dashboard</NavLink>
    </Nav.Item>
    <Nav.Item asChild>
      <NavLink to="/analytics">Analytics</NavLink>
    </Nav.Item>
  </Nav.Section>
  <Nav.Section title="Settings">
    <Nav.Item badge="3" asChild>
      <NavLink to="/notifications">Notifications</NavLink>
    </Nav.Item>
  </Nav.Section>
</Nav>
```

## Animate Component
- Scroll-triggered entrance animation wrapper
- Use for section entrances on landing pages
- Wraps content and animates it into view when it enters the viewport
- Props: `direction` (up, down, left, right), `delay` (stagger timing)
- Respects `prefers-reduced-motion` automatically, no extra work needed

### Animate example:
```tsx
<Animate direction="up">
  <Card title="Feature One">First card animates in</Card>
</Animate>
<Animate direction="up" delay={100}>
  <Card title="Feature Two">Second card staggers in</Card>
</Animate>
```

## Card Component
- Container with optional interactivity and tilt effects
- Props: `interactive` (hover state), `tilt` (enable tilt effect), `tiltDirection`, `padding`, `title`
- Use inside `<Grid>` for card layouts

### Card example:
```tsx
<Grid columns={3} gap="4">
  <Card title="Basic Card" padding="6">
    <Text>Simple content card</Text>
  </Card>
  <Card interactive tilt tiltDirection="left" title="Interactive Card">
    <Text>Hover for tilt effect</Text>
  </Card>
</Grid>
```

## Badge Component
- Inline status labels and indicators
- Props: `variant` (solid, outline), `size`, `icon`
- Use inside headings, nav items, or standalone

### Badge example:
```tsx
<HStack gap="2" align="center">
  <Heading level={3}>Features</Heading>
  <Badge variant="solid">New</Badge>
</HStack>
<Badge variant="outline" size="sm" icon={<Icon size="xs" />}>Beta</Badge>
```

## Icon Component
- SVG icon wrapper, always renders with `aria-hidden`
- When used standalone (not next to text), the parent element MUST have `aria-label`
- Props: `size`, `color`, `boxed` (background container), `shape`

### Icon example:
```tsx
<Icon size="md" color="accent">
  <SearchSvg />
</Icon>
<Icon size="sm" boxed shape="circle">
  <CheckSvg />
</Icon>
```

## Divider Component
- Visual separator between content sections
- Props: `variant` (default, squiggle), `orientation` (horizontal, vertical)

### Divider example:
```tsx
<Stack gap="6">
  <Text>Above the line</Text>
  <Divider />
  <Text>Below the line</Text>
</Stack>
<Divider variant="squiggle" />
```

## Toast Component
- Notification system using provider + hook pattern
- Wrap your app root in `<ToastProvider>`, then call `useToast()` in any component
- Toast options: `variant`, `title`, `description`

### Toast example:
```tsx
// In app root:
<ToastProvider>
  <App />
</ToastProvider>

// In any component:
const toast = useToast();
toast({ variant: "success", title: "Saved", description: "Changes saved successfully." });
toast({ variant: "error", title: "Error", description: "Something went wrong." });
```

## Textarea Component
- Multi-line text input, follows the same pattern as TextInput
- Wrap in `<FormField>` for automatic label/error/description association
- Integrates with FormField context the same way TextInput does

### Textarea example:
```tsx
<FormField label="Message" description="Tell us what you need">
  <Textarea placeholder="Type your message..." />
</FormField>
```

## Section Component
- Full-width page section with built-in `<Container>`
- Props: `bg` (background variant), `separator` (adds visual separator between sections)
- Use for structuring landing pages and content pages

### Section example:
```tsx
<Section bg="surface" separator>
  <SectionHeader title="Features" subtitle="What makes it great" />
  <Grid columns={3} gap="4">
    <Card title="Fast" />
    <Card title="Accessible" />
    <Card title="Beautiful" />
  </Grid>
</Section>
```

## SectionHeader Component
- Centered heading + subtitle combination
- Use inside `<Section>` for consistent page structure

### SectionHeader example:
```tsx
<SectionHeader title="Get Started" subtitle="Everything you need to build your next project" />
```

## Content Components

### Highlight
- Inline text emphasis with accent styling
```tsx
<Text>This is <Highlight>important</Highlight> information.</Text>
```

### CodeBlock
- Syntax-highlighted code display
```tsx
<CodeBlock language="tsx">{`const x = 1;`}</CodeBlock>
```

### Quote
- Styled blockquote for pull quotes and testimonials
```tsx
<Quote>Design is not just what it looks like. Design is how it works.</Quote>
```

## ParallaxLayout Component
- Fixed background scroll layout for hero sections and visual breaks
- Content scrolls over a fixed background

### ParallaxLayout example:
```tsx
<ParallaxLayout>
  <Section bg="default">
    <Heading level={1}>Welcome</Heading>
  </Section>
</ParallaxLayout>
```

## Common Patterns

### Building a form:
```tsx
<Stack gap="5">
  <FormField label="Candidate name" required>
    <TextInput placeholder="Full name" />
  </FormField>
  <FormField label="Role" description="Select the role you're hiring for">
    <Autocomplete onValueChange={setRole}>
      <Autocomplete.Trigger asChild>
        <TextInput placeholder="Select..." rightElement={<ChevronIcon />} />
      </Autocomplete.Trigger>
      <Autocomplete.Content>
        <Autocomplete.Input placeholder="Search roles..." />
        <Autocomplete.List>
          <Autocomplete.Item value="design-eng">Design Engineer</Autocomplete.Item>
          <Autocomplete.Item value="senior-fe">Senior Frontend</Autocomplete.Item>
        </Autocomplete.List>
        <Autocomplete.Empty>No roles found</Autocomplete.Empty>
      </Autocomplete.Content>
    </Autocomplete>
  </FormField>
</Stack>
```

### Modal with form:
```tsx
<Modal>
  <Modal.Trigger asChild>
    <Button variant="solid">Get in touch</Button>
  </Modal.Trigger>
  <Modal.Content>
    <Modal.Header>Let's talk</Modal.Header>
    <Modal.Body>
      <Stack gap="5">
        <FormField label="Name" required>
          <TextInput placeholder="Your name" />
        </FormField>
      </Stack>
    </Modal.Body>
    <Modal.Footer>
      <HStack gap="3" justify="end">
        <Modal.Close asChild><Button variant="ghost">Cancel</Button></Modal.Close>
        <Button variant="solid">Send</Button>
      </HStack>
    </Modal.Footer>
  </Modal.Content>
</Modal>
```
